{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480967"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:54:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"131"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/131"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.02,0.85,0.08,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92431"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"131","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/131"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"131"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75752"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"195"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6141"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92431"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department following a right knee injury sustained while playing soccer. While pivoting without contact from another player, she experienced a \u0027popping\u0027 sensation in her knee followed by immediate collapse and swelling. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right knee is diffusely swollen with a positive bulge sign. There is no bony tenderness or deformity. She can weight bear with difficulty. The knee is held in slight flexion at rest but has a full active range of movement with pain at the extremes. There is anterior-posterior instability of the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medial collateral ligament tear","Lateral meniscal tear","Anterior cruciate ligament tear","Medial meniscal tear","Patella fracture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of an anterior cruciate ligament injury. The mechanism of a non-contact pivoting injury, accompanied by a popping sensation and immediate swelling is highly characteristic. The immediate swelling indicates haemarthrosis from the richly vascularised \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior cruciate ligament\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial collateral ligament tear\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs with a valgus force to the knee and would present with medial joint line tenderness and instability in the coronal (medial-lateral) plane rather than the anterior-posterior plane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral meniscal tears\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial meniscal tears\u003C/strong\u003E typically present with delayed rather than immediate swelling, as the menisci are relatively avascular. They also usually have focal joint line tenderness, which is absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epatella fracture\u003C/strong\u003E would result in inability to actively extend the knee due to disruption of the extensor mechanism. This patient maintains active knee extension despite her injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of anterior-posterior instability on examination (positive anterior drawer or Lachman test) confirms the diagnosis of anterior cruciate ligament tear. MRI is usually performed to assess for associated injuries and guide management decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anterior cruciate ligament injury classically presents with a \u0027popping\u0027 sensation and immediate swelling after a non-contact pivoting injury","Immediate knee swelling suggests haemarthrosis, which occurs with anterior cruciate ligament tears due to its rich blood supply","Meniscal injuries typically present with delayed swelling and focal joint line tenderness"],"references":["Carek SM. Hip and Knee Injuries. Prim Care 2020; 47:115-31. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32014129/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75752"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"131"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75752","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75752"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T18:36:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T18:36:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"131"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92431"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationshi